                for those on the upper floors of the <ENAMEX TYPE="FAC">North Tower</ENAMEX> would have been a swift and
                extensive air rescue. Several factors made this impossible. Doors leading to the
                roof were kept locked for security reasons, and damage to software in the security
                command <ENAMEX TYPE="ORG_DESC">station</ENAMEX> prevented a lock release order from taking effect. Even if the doors
                had not been locked, structural and radiation hazards made the rooftops unsuitable
                staging areas for a large number of <ENAMEX TYPE="PER_DESC">civilians</ENAMEX>; and even if conditions permitted
                <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">general</ENAMEX> helicopter <ENAMEX TYPE="PRODUCT_DESC">evacuations</ENAMEX>-which was not the case-only several <ENAMEX TYPE="PER_DESC">people</ENAMEX> could be
                lifted at a time.
            The <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">WTC</ENAMEX> lacked any plan for evacuation of <ENAMEX TYPE="PER_DESC">civilians</ENAMEX> on upper floors of the <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">WTC</ENAMEX> in the
